ProtectWave VPN – Complete Technical Documentation
1. Product Overview

Product Name: ProtectWave VPN
Purpose: Secure and private internet access. Users can choose free mode (with ads) or paid subscription (ad-free).
Target Users: Free users and paid subscribers.

2. Core Features

VPN connect/disconnect
Server selection (start with 3 servers: USA, Germany, Singapore)
Paid subscription → ad-free experience
Free users → optional login, ads displayed
Subscription status check
Login/logout functionality
Networking & routing essentials
Data isolation per user

3. Feature Prioritization

Priority 1 – Core

VPN connect/disconnect
Server selection
Paid subscription login → ad-free experience

Priority 2 – Important

Connection status
Password reset
Data isolation

Priority 3 – Optional

Auto-reconnect
Analytics
Additional servers

4. Tech Stack

Backend: Go (Golang) – fast, secure, networking-friendly
Database: PostgreSQL – stores users, subscriptions, tokens
Cloud: AWS – hosts backend, database, VPN servers
VPN Protocol: WireGuard – encrypted traffic

5. API Contracts
5.1 User Registration (Paid Users)

Endpoint: POST /register
Request Body:

{
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}


Response:

{
  "message": "User registered successfully"
}

5.2 User Login

Endpoint: POST /login
Request Body:

{
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}


Response:

{
  "token": "sample_token_value",
  "subscription": "paid"
}

5.3 Get User Profile

Endpoint: GET /profile
Headers:

Authorization: Bearer sample_token_value


Response:

{
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "subscription": "paid"
}

5.4 Get VPN Server List

Endpoint: GET /servers
Response:

[
  { "id": 1, "country": "UK" },
  { "id": 2, "country": "Germany" },
  { "id": 3, "country": "Portugal" }
]

5.5 Connect to VPN Server

Endpoint: POST /connect
Request Body:

{
  "server_id": 2
}


Response:

{
  "status": "connected"
}

5.6 Disconnect VPN

Endpoint: POST /disconnect
Response:

{
  "status": "disconnected"
}

5.7 Subscription Status

Endpoint: GET /subscription
Headers:

Authorization: Bearer sample_token_value


Response:

{
  "plan": "paid",
  "ads": false
}

5.8 Logout

Endpoint: POST /logout
Headers:

Authorization: Bearer sample_token_value


Response:

{
  "message": "Logged out successfully"
}


Notes:

Free users can access server list and connect without login
Paid users require authentication token
Tokens are used for secure communication
APIs include both our custom APIs and optional external APIs (payment, ads, email verification)

6. System Architecture (Conceptual)
Client (App) → Backend (APIs) → Database
                        ↘
                         VPN Servers → Internet


Flow Example (Login):

Client → Backend (/login) → Database → Backend → Response → Client

7. Additional Notes

Free users: ads displayed, no login required
Paid users: must login, no ads
Tokens: digital key for paid users
Traffic: encrypted through VPN server (WireGuard)
External APIs used for: payments, ads, email verification

8. Future References

Backend implementation will follow API contracts
Database schema: users table, server table, subscription table
VPN server setup: WireGuard protocol, routing, encryption
